---

<CalculatorLayout calculator={calculator} cluster={cluster} intro={intro} lastUpdated={lastUpdated} authorName={authorName} authorUrl={authorUrl} shareImage={shareImage}>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(howToJsonLd)} slot="head" />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbJsonLd)} slot="head" />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(personJsonLd)} slot="head" />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(softwareAppJsonLd)} slot="head" />

  <!-- Desktop sticky TOC in the right sidebar column -->
  <TableOfContents items={tocItems} variant="sidebar" slot="sidebar" />

  <!-- Calculator tool — immediately after intro, visible without scrolling -->
  <VegetableYieldCalculator client:load />

  <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-bark-500">
    Part of the <a href="/clusters/spacing-and-planting/" class="text-moss-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-moss-900">Spacing & Planting cluster</a> — pairs well with our <a href="/calculators/plant-spacing-calculator/" class="text-moss-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-moss-900">Plant Spacing Calculator</a> for planning how many plants fit first.
  </p>

  <!-- Mobile TOC accordion — below the calculator, collapsed by default, hidden on desktop -->
  <TableOfContents items={tocItems} variant="accordion" />

  <LeadMagnetForm
    client:load
    listId={leadMagnet.listId}
    clusterName={leadMagnet.clusterName}
    description={`A one-page PDF of the ${cluster.name.toLowerCase()} math from this site, emailed once.`}
  />

  <article class="prose prose-bark mt-8 max-w-none prose-headings:font-display prose-headings:text-bark-900 prose-h2:mt-12 prose-h2:scroll-mt-24 prose-h2:text-2xl prose-h2:font-semibold prose-h3:text-lg prose-h3:font-semibold prose-a:text-moss-700 prose-strong:text-bark-900">

    <h2 id="how-do-you-estimate-vegetable-garden-yield">How Do You Estimate Vegetable Garden Yield?</h2>
    <p>
      This <strong>vegetable yield calculator</strong> works from published per-plant yield figures — how many pounds a single plant of a given crop typically produces over a full growing season. Multiply that by your plant count (or estimate plant count from your bed&rsquo;s square footage) and you get an estimated total harvest weight.
    </p>
    <p>
      Real yield varies a lot from these averages. Variety matters &mdash; a cherry tomato plant can produce nearly double the fruit weight of a standard slicing tomato. Climate and length of growing season matter, since more warm weeks generally means more harvest. Soil quality, consistent watering, and pest pressure all shift real-world results up or down, sometimes significantly. Treat every number here as a reasonable planning average, not a guarantee &mdash; your actual garden will tell you its own numbers after a season or two.
    </p>
    <p>
      The calculator handles two common starting points: if you already know how many plants you have, use <strong>Number of Plants</strong> mode directly. If you&rsquo;re still planning a bed and thinking in square footage, use <strong>Growing Area</strong> mode, which estimates plant count from typical spacing for that crop first.
    </p>

    <h2 id="vegetable-yield-reference-chart">Vegetable Yield Reference Chart</h2>
    <p>
      Per-plant yield estimates below are derived from LSU AgCenter&rsquo;s published per-100-foot-row garden yield data, divided by typical plants per row at standard spacing (see Sources below). Crops LSU reports by count rather than weight (heads, ears) are converted using typical average unit weights, noted in the table.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Crop</th>
          <th>Est. yield per plant</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Tomato</td><td>~5.0 lbs</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tomato (cherry)</td><td>~9.0 lbs</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Squash (winter)</td><td>~4.5 lbs</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Cucumber</td><td>~1.7 lbs</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Squash (summer)</td><td>~1.6 lbs</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Pepper (bell)</td><td>~1.9 lbs</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Lettuce (head)</td><td>~1.0 lb (1 head)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Broccoli</td><td>~0.8 lb (main head + side shoots)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Corn</td><td>~0.7 lb (1 ear with husk)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Onion</td><td>~0.7 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Carrot</td><td>~0.4 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Spinach</td><td>~0.2 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Bean (pole)</td><td>~0.15 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Bean (bush)</td><td>~0.1 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Radish</td><td>~0.05 lb</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      Fruiting crops that vine or branch heavily (winter squash, cucumbers, indeterminate tomatoes) produce far more per plant than crops harvested as a single unit (lettuce, broccoli, radishes) &mdash; that gap is real and consistent across most yield data, not an artifact of this particular chart.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>A note on tomato varieties:</strong> the table above uses a single ~5 lb figure for standard tomatoes, but variety type makes a significant difference. <strong>Indeterminate</strong> varieties (most heirlooms, many beefsteaks, most cherry types) keep growing and setting fruit all season &mdash; they typically yield <strong>15&ndash;25 lbs per plant</strong> over a full season, though that harvest is spread out over many weeks. <strong>Determinate</strong> varieties (Roma, most paste types, many modern slicers) stop growing at a set height and ripen their fruit in a concentrated window, typically yielding <strong>8&ndash;12 lbs per plant</strong> but delivering most of it within a few weeks. If you know which type you&rsquo;re growing, adjust your expectation accordingly &mdash; the ~5 lb default in the calculator is a conservative cross-variety average that can substantially underestimate a well-grown indeterminate plant.
    </p>

    <h2 id="how-much-to-plant-per-person">How Much to Plant Per Person</h2>
    <p>
      The yield calculator answers &ldquo;what will my garden produce?&rdquo; &mdash; but the companion question is &ldquo;how much should I plant to feed my family?&rdquo; These are per-person planting guidelines derived from typical garden productivity and average household consumption. They assume a reasonable growing season; succession-sown crops (marked below) require replanting every 2&ndash;3 weeks to sustain harvest through the season.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Crop</th>
          <th>Recommended per person</th>
          <th>Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Tomato</td><td>2&ndash;3 plants</td><td>Use 2 plants of an indeterminate variety; add a third for preserving or sauce. Determinate types: 3&ndash;4 plants for equivalent fresh yield.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Pepper (bell)</td><td>2&ndash;3 plants</td><td>3&ndash;5 plants if you want enough for freezing.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Cucumber</td><td>2 plants</td><td>Cucumbers set fruit fast &mdash; 2 plants can outpace most households at peak; 1 plant is workable if space is tight.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Zucchini / summer squash</td><td>1&ndash;2 plants</td><td>One healthy plant routinely produces more than a single household can eat; two plants ensures backup if one underperforms.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Bean (bush or pole)</td><td>5 ft of row</td><td>Succession-sow every 2&ndash;3 weeks for continuous harvest rather than one large flush.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Lettuce</td><td>3 ft of row</td><td>Succession-sow; a single row planting bolts quickly in warm weather.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Carrot</td><td>2&ndash;3 ft of row</td><td>Thin to proper spacing &mdash; crowded carrots stay small regardless of row length.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Beet</td><td>2 ft of row</td><td>Both roots and greens are edible; factor that into your estimate if you use both.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Spinach</td><td>3 ft of row</td><td>Bolts quickly in heat; sow in early spring and again in fall for two usable windows.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Broccoli</td><td>3&ndash;5 plants</td><td>Each plant gives one main head plus smaller side shoots over several weeks.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Onion</td><td>25&ndash;50 sets</td><td>Scale up if storing for winter; onions keep well and bulk planting is worthwhile.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Corn</td><td>10&ndash;15 plants</td><td>Must be planted in a block (not a single row) for adequate pollination &mdash; minimum block size is at least 4 rows wide.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      These figures target fresh eating, not preservation. If you plan to can, freeze, or dry a crop, roughly double or triple the planting for that crop. A family of four multiplies each figure above by four, though households that eat a particular vegetable very frequently will want to scale further.
    </p>

    <h2 id="worked-example">Worked Example</h2>
    <p>
      Say you&rsquo;re growing <strong>6 tomato plants</strong> this season.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Per-plant yield:</strong> ~5.0 lbs (from the reference chart above).</li>
      <li><strong>Total plants:</strong> 6.</li>
      <li><strong>Estimated total yield:</strong> 6 &times; 5.0 = <strong>30 lbs</strong> for the season.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Switch to <strong>Growing Area</strong> mode with a 24 sq ft bed of tomatoes instead (at 4 sq ft per plant): the calculator estimates 6 plants fit, then applies the same 5.0 lbs-per-plant figure for the same 30 lb estimate &mdash; the two modes agree because they&rsquo;re built on the same underlying per-plant number, just starting from a different known quantity.
    </p>

    <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common Mistakes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Expecting textbook yields without accounting for local conditions.</strong> Published averages assume reasonably good soil, consistent water, and a full growing season. A hot, dry summer or nutrient-poor soil can easily cut real yield well below the estimate.</li>
      <li><strong>Overcrowding, which reduces per-plant yield.</strong> Cramming plants closer than the spacing these estimates assume means more competition for light, water, and nutrients &mdash; often producing less total harvest, not more, despite the extra plants.</li>
      <li><strong>Not succession planting for continuous harvest.</strong> A single planting of a fast-maturing crop like lettuce or radishes gives one harvest window; staggering plantings every couple of weeks extends the total season yield well past what a one-time estimate suggests.</li>
    </ul>

    <FAQBlock id="vegetable-yield-calculator-faq" heading="Vegetable Yield Calculator FAQ" faqs={faqs} />

    <h2 id="sources-and-further-reading">Sources &amp; further reading</h2>
    <p>
      Per-plant yield figures are derived from <a href="https://www.lsuagcenter.com/topics/lawn_garden/home_gardening/vegetables/expected-vegetable-garden-yields" rel="noopener">LSU AgCenter&rsquo;s Expected Vegetable Garden Yields</a>, which publishes expected yields per 100-foot row for a good Southern home garden. We divided those figures by typical plants per row at standard in-row spacing to get a per-plant estimate. As LSU AgCenter notes, actual yields vary with season, care, soil, pest pressure, and cultivar &mdash; these are planning estimates, not guarantees. For more on how we build and verify the formulas behind every calculator on this site, see our <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>.
    </p>

    <RelatedCalculatorsList id="related-calculators" items={[
      { name: 'Spacing & Planting cluster', url: '/clusters/spacing-and-planting/', anchorText: 'Spacing & Planting cluster', note: 'more layout and timing calculators for planning your garden.' },
      { name: 'Plant Spacing Calculator', url: '/calculators/plant-spacing-calculator/', note: 'figure out how many plants fit first, then estimate what they’ll produce.' },
      { name: 'Raised Bed Soil Calculator', url: '/calculators/raised-bed-soil-calculator/', note: 'plan your raised bed depth and soil volume before you plant.' },
    ]} />

    <p class="mt-12 text-sm text-bark-500">
      Last updated: {formattedDate}.
    </p>
  </article>
</CalculatorLayout>
